Let $f: S_1 \to S_2$ and $g: S_2 \to S_3$ be [[Definition:Surjection|surjections]].\nThen:
{{begin-eqn}}
{{eqn | l = \forall z \in S_3: \exists y \in S_2: \map g y
| r = z
| c = {{Defof|Surjection}}
}}\n{{eqn | ll= \leadsto
| l = \exists x \in S_1: \map f x
| r = y
| c = {{Defof|Surjection}}
}}
{{end-eqn}}\nBy definition of a [[Definition:Composition of Mappings|composite mapping]]:
:$\map {g \circ f} x = \map g {\map f x} = \map g y = z$\nHence $g \circ f$ is [[Definition:Surjection|surjective]].\n{{qed}}

